defs: Transfer of heat through direct contact between particles of matter
Heat flows from higher temperature region to lower temperature region through a material
examples: A metal spoon getting hot when placed in hot soup
Heat traveling from a stove burner through a pot to cook food

defs: Heat transfer through the movement of fluids (liquids or gases)
Warmer, less dense fluid rises while cooler, denser fluid sinks
examples: Boiling water creates circular currents as hot water rises
Sea breeze and land breeze patterns

defs: Transfer of energy through electromagnetic waves
Does not require a medium; can travel through a vacuum
examples: Heat from a campfire that you can feel without touching

defs: A material that allows heat or electricity to pass through easily
Has loosely bound electrons that can move freely
examples: Copper wire used in electrical circuits

defs: A material that resists the flow of heat or electricity
Has tightly bound electrons that cannot move easily
examples: Woolen clothing that keeps you warm

defs: State when two objects in contact reach the same temperature
No net heat flow occurs between objects at thermal equilibrium
examples: Ice melting in a glass of water until both reach the same temperature
A thermometer reading stabilizing when measuring body temperature

defs: The ability of a surface to emit thermal radiation
Ranges from 0 (perfect reflector) to 1 (perfect emitter/black body)
examples: Black surfaces have high emissivity and radiate heat efficiently
Shiny metal surfaces have low emissivity

defs: The process of taking in energy from radiation
Energy absorbed is converted to thermal energy in the material
examples: Dark asphalt absorbing sunlight and becoming hot
Solar panels absorbing sunlight to generate electricity

defs: Amount of heat energy required to raise the temperature of 1 kg of a substance by 1 degree C
Different materials have different specific heat capacities
examples: Water has a high specific heat, so it heats up slowly
Sand has a low specific heat and heats up quickly in sunlight

defs: A measure of how well a material conducts heat
Materials with high thermal conductivity transfer heat rapidly
examples: Diamond has very high thermal conductivity
Styrofoam has very low thermal conductivity

defs: Materials that allow heat or electricity to pass through easily
Multiple materials with loosely bound electrons
examples: Metals like copper, aluminum, and silver
Iron and steel are commonly used

defs: Materials that resist the flow of heat or electricity
Multiple materials with tightly bound electrons
Uses expansion of liquids or digital sensors
Water freezes at 0 and boils at 100
Temperature scale used mainly in USA
Water freezes at 32 and boils at 212
